[Event "Baker Bridge - 2-Over-1 Game Force"]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "1"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "E:9.JT7.T987.KJ962 AJT62.A62.QJ.T87 Q8743..K6532.Q53 K5.KQ98543.A4.A4"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "6H"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "E"]
Pass 1S Pass 2H Pass 3H Pass 4NT Pass 5H =1= Pass 5NT =2= Pass 6H =3= Pass Pass Pass
[Note "1:2 keycards, no trump Q"]
[Note "2:king ask"]
[Note "3:no kings lower than hearts"]
{South opens 1\S.  What do you respond with? 
You have a powerhouse, plenty strong enough to jump-shift. But playing 2/1 it's usually simpler when you make the 2/1 response, and save your jumping for later - if at all. So just bid 2\H, knowing South must keep the bidding open.
South responds 3\h, setting the trump suit.   
Now you are definitely  interested in slam.  Since you have controls in all the side suits, you go right to keycard Blackwood, using the 1430 system.  Partner responds 5\H.   

Partner's 5\H shows two keycards without the trump queen.  But we have the other 3 keycards, and the trump queen.  If partner has the two minor kings we might have a grand.  We ask about these with our 5NT bid.  Unfortunately, partner responds 6\H (playing specific kings, this denies any kings lower than hearts).  We will pass and play there.
This is a good slam, cold if East makes any opening lead other than a \C. With a \C lead, North will have to pull trumps and play to discard a loser on the \ST.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "2"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "NS"]
[Deal "E:A.AQJ753.742.KJ4 K875.86.AT9.T532 QJ2.KT.KQ865.Q87 T9643.942.J3.A96"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "4H"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "E"]
1H Pass 2D Pass 2H Pass 4H Pass Pass Pass
{How do you start this action? [Bid 1H]
You open 1\H and partner responds 2\D.  What do you rebid? 
Partner's 2 over 1 bid sets up a game force.
You have a good-looking hand, but you need to find a trump suit before showing extra strength, so she bids just 2\H.  You are in a game forcing auction, so partner won't pass you.
Partner now jumps to 4\h.  What do you do now? 

Partner's jump to 4\h is Fast Arrival - showing a minimum game forcing hand.  Even though we have extra values, this won't be enough for slam opposite 13 or so points.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "N:AQ862.T4.K65.K87 T743.862.AQJ7.A3 J.KQJ753.432.Q54 K95.A9.T98.JT962"]
[Declarer "S"]
[Contract "2H"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "N"]
1S Pass 1NT Pass 2C Pass 2H Pass Pass Pass
{North opens 1\S.  
You have 11 points, enough to respond 2\H in standard bidding, but not when using 2/1. So we use the forcing 1NT.  North rebids 2\c.   This only promises 3 clubs, so is really just there so we can better describe our hand with our second bid.  What do we bid now? 

Now we can bid 2H, and it shows 6+\hs and only 6-10 points. 
North was forced to reply to 1NT, but he is not forced to bid again. With his minimum hand and a tolerance for partner's suit he just passes and the partnership ends up in a reasonable contract.
This hand demonstrates one of the benefits of Forcing 1NT. In standard bidding South's first response would be 2\H, and North would have to bid again, probably 2NT. The partnership might go even higher but in any case would probably not reach a good contract.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "4"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "All"]
[Deal "E:AQ862.A4.95.AK87 J9.JT986.Q874.Q6 K.K753.AT32.J954 T7543.Q2.KJ6.T32"]
[Declarer "W"]
[Contract "3NT"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "E"]
1S Pass 1NT Pass 2C Pass 2NT Pass 3NT Pass Pass Pass
{East opens 1\S. What should you bid? 
You have 11 points, enough to respond 2\C, (or 2\D), in standard bidding, but not when using 2/1. So you bid 1NT, showing 6-12 points.
East rebids 2\c.  Again, this doesn't promise more than 3\c - it's just leaving room for us to describe our hand with our second bid.  What do we bid now? 

We know East doesn't have 4 \Hs, so we show our above-minimum hand by bidding 2NT.
East has extra values and raises to 3NT.
East is happy to play Notrump. He assumes we must have something useful in \Ds and bids 3NT.
3NT seems to be a good contract. There are 8 top tricks and possibilities for a ninth winner in either \Ss, \Ds, or, (the best chance), \Cs.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "5"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "N:862.AQJ753.95.A2 J73.2.AQ764.K963 K95.T6.KT32.JT54 AQT4.K984.J8.Q87"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "2H"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "N"]
1H Pass 1NT Pass 2H Pass Pass Pass
{North opens 1\H. What should we bid? 
We respond 1NT, just as in standard bidding. The difference is that in this case the 1NT response is forcing on North.
North rebids \hs, promising at least a 6-card suit.  

You have nothing to say over 2\H except pass.
Notice that this is the same bidding and same final contract that would have been reached with standard bidding. Using 2/1 is often like that.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "6"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:AQT95.T96.KT86.A 643.KQJ32.J32.T8 KJ2.874.AQ975.Q2 87.A5.4.KJ976543"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "4S"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "E"]
1S Pass 2D Pass 3D Pass 4S Pass Pass Pass
{How do you open the bidding? 
You open 1\S. West responds 2\D, a natural 2/1 force to game.  What do you rebid? 

You cannot rebid your \ss, but you have have decent support for partner's \ds, so raise to 3\d.  You are in a game forcing auction so it won't end there.
West always intended to play a \S contract. He now bids 4\S, using Fast Arrival to indicate he has no slam aspirations.
4\S is cold, and if the defenders don't take their \H tricks immediately you will make an overtrick.}

